title: "Structural Cognitive Runtime (SCR): From Structural Cognitive Emergence to Collective Learning Table and the Humanistic Question of ASI"
type: software
authors:

* family-names: "Tan"
  given-names: "Sizhe"
  affiliation: "Independent Researcher"
  repository-code: "https://github.com/sizhet/Structural-Cognitive-Runtime-SCR"
  url: "https://github.com/sizhet/Structural-Cognitive-Runtime-SCR"
  abstract: >
  Structural Cognitive Runtime (SCR) is a research repository in the Structural
  Intelligence line that asks what kind of runtime is needed once structural
  cognitive emergence has already taken place. If Structural Cognitive Emergence
  (SCE) focused on concept formation, gap emergence, and Why-generation, SCR
  focuses on the runtime layer that follows: a system capable of Gap-Why
  diagnosis, Developmental Update / Structural Asset Update, collective
  human-AI learning, structural data accumulation, and explicit humanistic
  boundary reflection.

The repository is organized around several connected layers. It introduces a
Gap-Why Engine that expands Why-generation from narrow code-gap handling to
multi-family structural gap diagnosis; a Developmental Update / Structural
Asset Update layer through which a runtime can update, consolidate, and
reorganize the structural assets that future reasoning and future learning
depend on; a Collective Learning Table as a mixed human-AI learning
environment; and the extension of that environment toward a Structural Data
Engine and a Circle of Approval. The repository also includes The Humanistic
Question of ASI, which asks under what humanistic, philosophical, and
governance conditions such a runtime should be allowed to grow.

SCR is not presented as a finished AGI architecture. Its contribution is to
make the runtime layer between structural emergence and larger mixed human-AI
developmental systems explicit: the layer where a system detects structural
gaps, updates its own structural assets, supports collective learning, and
eventually must face the humanistic and civilizational conditions under which
its growth remains legitimate.
